      "Training Intercept:  [  9.49385005   1.91823857 -11.41208863]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# i. Use sklearn to train a LogisticRegression model on the training set\n",
    "train_model = LogisticRegression().fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "# ii. For a sample datapoint, predict the probabilities for each possible class\n",
    "print(\"Results of Training Predictions: \" , train_model.predict_proba(X_test[:1]))\n",
    "\n",
    "# iii. Report on the score for Logistic regression model, what does the score measure?\n",
    "print(\"Training Score: \", train_model.score(X_test, y_test))\n",
    "print(\"View Markdown below for explaination.\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# iv. Extract the coefficents and intercepts for the boundary line(s)\n",
    "print(\"Training Coef: \", train_model.coef_)\n",
    "print(\"Training Intercept: \",train_model.intercept_)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# iii. Report on the score for Logistic regression model, what does the score measure?\n",
    "The score measures how well the model performs with unknown data (the testing data). The higher the value the more accurate it can predict it. The score is determined by giving our model a dataset of unknown features. The model predicts what the corresponding labels are. With the given correct labels for the given x features, the score is determined by how many labels the model was able to correctly predict.\n",
    "Our current training model has a score of 1. This can mean that it was able to perfectly identify the unknown data that we have given it. On the other hand, in somecases giving the model an unfiltered dataset could cause a score of 1."
   ]
  },
  {
